segments.text: Oh, I wanted to talk a little bit about the New Deal and Roosevelt.
The president comes in in 1933, and your family is basically a conservative one, yet he fundamentally changed American government and the system with the New Deal.
I was wondering about your political persuasion.
What did your father think?
What did you people think about the New Deal, about Roosevelt?
Did it have any impact?
Did it seem like it had any impact on you at all?
I can't remember any kind of impact.
As party affiliations, you know, we were all Democrats, but I don't recall Papa ever saying
you know, one way or another that it was the right thing or the wrong thing, because he wasn't that really involved in politics.
In other words, your father was not only not involved in politics, but he was not, he never received any federal assistance like so many other Americans did during that time.
No.
Wish he had, but he hadn't.
No, he didn't receive any federal assistance at all, and didn't seek it.
No, he didn't seek it.
And I don't remember making, ever remember him making any comments about
want to take advantage of the New Deal thing.
He wasn't politically motivated that way.
Just work.
Yeah, right.
Now, you never thought of going to another institution besides A&M?
Well, I had an offer to go to Baylor University on a scholarship.
You did?
Well, tell me about that.
Well, my high school coach was a Baylor graduate.
And he wanted me to go to Baylor.
But I told him, I'm sorry, but Papa wants me to go to A&M.
And I'll go there if I have to work.
But Baylor is basically a conservative school.
And so your father didn't, nevertheless, he still thought.
Said A&M because of the military aspect.
OK.
Speaking of military, did you ever think of going to West Point?
Not till I got to A&M.
After my freshman year, I thought about West Point because my roommate, my sophomore year, had an appointment to West Point.
Who was that?
It was Lloyd White from Texarkana, Texas.
And he couldn't pass the physical.
His chest didn't meet the required measurement.
And so they told him to come back in a year, and they would reconsider his application.
And so he was talking to me as my roommate my sophomore year to go with him.
And I gave it some consideration.
And every morning, I would make him get up.
He was a little bitty fellow.
I'd make him get up and get in front of the window and do deep breathing exercises every morning.
And so he passed the physical, but then he also had a chance to go to Annapolis, so he went to Annapolis instead.
Instead of Army, he went to, instead of West Point, he went to Annapolis.
And that was the only time I ever thought about going to any kind of military academy, was his .
Okay, what were your first impressions when you arrived at A&M?
1939, wasn't it?
Right.
It was different.
Had you ever been, ever visited the campus before?
I visited one time prior to that.
I went to see my brothers.
They were in Mitchell Hall.
And I'm sorry, at Lauren Puryear.
Jimmy was in Lauren Puryear.
And I was the only one to see him.
And I didn't see much of the campus then because we
went to see him, and then we went to the basketball game that night, and then we'd come on home the next day.
But my first impression of A&M was just great.
I couldn't believe it, that I was going to come to A&M.
Not because of the school, because of the facilities.
You know, my own bed, my own room, my shower, and...
In other words, it was almost an increase of living standards for you, would you say that?
I would say that, sure.
Matter of fact, one reason why we love the Y so much is because the first shower I took in my life was at the YMCA.
When I was growing up, I can remember, Terry, I can remember when I was a little kid,
Mama washed me in a wash tub.
We didn't have really much.
You didn't have indoor plumbing.
We had indoor plumbing, but we didn't have a tub.
We had indoor plumbing, but we didn't find any.
Then Papa improved the bathroom facilities.
But I never had a shower at home.
I always had a tub.
The first shower I took was at the Y. I really, really love the Y. Oh, yeah, I do.
All my brothers love the Y.
But back to your question about A&M, I was just happy to be there.
Just delighted to be there.
Felt so good.
How, in what way, I mean besides the fact that you had your own room or you know you shared a room and you had really good facilities, what do you mean it just felt good to be there?
I knew I was going to get a good education.
I was going to get a good education, and A&M was a man's school.
Well, did you like that idea?
That it was all-male school?
It didn't bother me.
Did you like it or dislike it?
Liked it.
I liked it because it was all-male school.
I guess because as a kid in high school,
I didn't have any money or car or anything to take the girls out, so I didn't really chase the girls.
I had girlfriends all right, but I didn't chase them and didn't entertain them like I would today if I had a chance.
But just being all military and all male and getting an education at A&M,
I was so happy.
I thought it was the greatest thing that ever happened to me was to go to A&M as a freshman.
Just great, just.
I was in awe by it, really.
Now what unit were you placed in?
I was in A Battery Field Artillery my freshman year.
And then my, the rest of my three years I was in H Battery Field Artillery.
I was in the same battery my brothers were in.
Janelle and Jimmy were in A battery.
And then when Andrew came up the next year, he got in A battery.
All four of us were in A battery, field artillery.
And then the school moved me over to H battery.
They reorganized field artillery.
So I stayed in H battery the rest of the term.
Tell me about hazing.
What would you want to know about hazing?
Well, what kind of hazing?
What did they do?
They whipped my butt with a board.
That's what they did.
And I shook their hand when I got through and said, thank you.
And we had rap sessions, sophomore on top of freshman.
And they aired us out in the middle of the night.
Get us out of the dormitory.
Hazing in respect from upperclassmen to freshmen.
Make us walk down the hall crab-like until we were about to die.
Made us sit in the corner on top of a sword.
Really?
An imaginary sword.
Oh.
With your arms extended like this.
knee bends and stuff.
And then we'd do push-ups and knee bends and all kinds of exercises.
Thinking back on it, did you think that the hazing that you had in the late 30s and early 40s, do you think that was a positive or a negative aspect of A&M?
At the time, I think it's positive.
It was positive.
I thought it was part of the school, part of the tradition, part of the training.
Mm-hmm.
It didn't bother me.
Oh, it didn't.
It did not bother me.
I took it and didn't like it.
I took it.
I think this is the training.
I didn't like it at all.
I used to fuss and gripe about it when I got along.
But I'd say, well, this is part of the system, part of the education, part of the discipline and the core.
You accepted it?
Accepted it.
Tell me about your colleagues.
What kind of people were they?
My contemporaries?
Yeah, your student colleagues.
People in the Corps.
The freshmen or the... Yeah.
When you first got there, you were a freshman.
Well, everybody like I was.
They weren't quite as physically active as I was.
I was out for the freshman basketball team, so
In fact, I was out for the freshman football team.
Made the freshman football team quit.
Really?
Yeah.
Why'd you quit?
I got hurt.
John Kimbrough and Robinette and Arnold Pannell and that bunch, they just ran over me a couple of times, and I was just too small for them.
My picture's in the annual on the freshman team, freshman football team.
At that time, if you're on a part-time scholarship, any kind, you played all the sports.
All of them?
All of them.
So as a basketball scholarship, I had to play football.
And then- Even if you didn't- No, no, I never played football in my life.
Do you remember an interview about high school?
I was a cheerleader, and I was basketball and swimming.
I never played football, and made the first team.
Gee, what position?
Backfield.
Willie Zablack, Dub, Dub, Willie Zablack's now coaching at Texas.
Mm-hm.
And Dub Sibley and all this bunch of, we were all in the backfield.
Dub was the center.
But I made the team and didn't like it.
Didn't want to play.
Papa didn't know I was playing.
Papa knew I was playing.
Boy, he whipped me good.
But he didn't want me to play football.
But I had to.
He didn't want you to get beat up?
Yeah.
He thought I was too small.
I didn't weigh but 155 pounds and 5 foot 8.
And so...
In the middle of the practice one day, Ernie Panel and Marshall Robinette, leading interference for John Kimbrough, just ran over me.
And I said, this is it.
I'm not going to play.
And I got up off the field and I walked towards the locker room and Coach Homer Norton, head coach, hollered at me, hey, Cokie, where are you going?
And all I could do was wave.
He said, come on back here.
And I just, no.
So when I got to the
When I got to the locker room, Bubba Dimmitt, the trainer says, here, take my stuff.
Don't ever give me an oblong ball anymore.
I want a round ball, basketball.
And I quit.
And Coach Norton was about to take away my basketball scholarship.
Really?
Yeah.
Because they wanted me to play.
And Coach Corot, my basketball coach, who was also the football coach, intervened and said, no.
let him just play basketball.
So I got relieved of that.
And so my contemporaries were all, they were just typical high school kids coming in.
I was about a year or two older than they were.
And so we got along great though.
Do you remember what kind of benefits you got from a part-time scholarship?
Yeah, I got
$20 a month.
And also, they gave me a job in a mess hall.
I was a mess hall waiter for four years.
Even after I got more money playing basketball later on, I stayed in with my job as a waiter in a mess hall.
I liked it.
And the people I waited on liked me, so I enjoyed it.
They took one football scholarship, Terry, and split it up into five basketball scholarships.
That's what they did.
Scholarships for A&M basketball were not like the other day.
No.
Oh, no.
But I had a good group of freshman classmates.
Could you live on 20 a month?
No.
The meals were $35 a month.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
And how about tuition?
Did they give you tuition?
They gave me my tuition.
So $20 a month and they gave you a free tuition?
Tuition.
But you had to buy your books and run the board.
And expenses and everything.
And then I worked in the mess hall.
And then I did other odd jobs.
Took up tickets to football games.
What position did you play in the basketball team?
I was a guard.
I was a quarterback, what we called quarterback guard then.
I brought the ball down and controlled the game, controlled the passing, and passed it into our postman.
I haven't looked at those figures, but how good was the team back then?
Oh, we beat the national champs in 1941.
We beat Rice University.
They were the national champs.
Really?
And we beat them.
We were about, I think that year we came out third in the conference.
We had a pretty good team.
We didn't have any substitutes.
In fact, we were called the Five Ironmen of Southwest Conference.
Five of us played all the time.
You only had five people?
Well, first five.
Then we had about four or five substitutes.
Very much.
In fact, I played every game, every minute of the game when I didn't get fouled out.
I hold the record for the most fouls in Southwest California.
I was all over them.
You tackled them.
I was all over them.
I was all over them.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, whenever the coach wanted to keep somebody from shooting, he'd put me on him, and I'd hold him down.
I was a good guard, as short as I was.
I could hold a man down, keep him from shooting.
and do a pretty good job not hurting him, just guarding him around.
Now let's turn back to the Corps for a minute.
I want to find out what were the things that you liked about the Corps and what were the things that you disliked about the Corps?
I liked the, I didn't mind the marching, marching to meals.
I liked that and I liked the chain of command.
You mean you liked the idea that you always knew who was...
In charge.
In charge.
Yeah.
Like the first sergeant, juniors, you know, and seniors.
I liked that.
And...
I just...
I just liked it.
Cool.
I just really liked it, you know.
Now my dislikes were... See, I...
I disliked one of the things, they didn't let us study enough.
They didn't let us study enough.
I wanted to study and god dang the damn sophomores would come in and harass us and send us on details.
Just didn't study enough.
And I was a pre-med student, so I was taking science courses.
You thought that you were going to be a medical doctor?
Don't kid me.
I got a degree in science.
Yeah, I know that.
Yeah, yeah.
And I planned to be a doctor.
Of course, my mama influenced me to be a doctor.
Oh, I didn't know that.
Yeah, her grandfather was a doctor in Greece.
And so you went there with the idea of not becoming an engineer and not staying in the military, but with the idea of becoming a doctor.
Well, that's right.
And what dissuaded you away from becoming a medical doctor?
The Army.
They, of course when I graduated, I went to the Army and when I come back, I tried to get in medical school.
When I got back, oh yeah.
Which one?
I tried Texas, Baylor, Tulane, Creighton up in Des Moines.
Des Moines, in Iowa.
Oh, okay.
Yeah.
No, I mean Omaha, Omaha, Nebraska.
Creighton's up there.
I tried that because I had a friend, doctor, who tried to get me in.
Oh, that's a sad story.
I don't know if I'll tell you or not.
I got accepted to Bail a Man.
You did?
Well, why didn't you go?
I was accepted in April, and in 1st of June, I gave... What year was this?
And they wrote me a letter.
They said, we'd like for you to come back to see Dean Morrison.
He wants to have an interview with you.
So I went back over there to Houston.
It was in
And he told me they overpicked the class.
And I was the last five they overpicked.
So I couldn't enroll.
I said, OK, if I was overpicked, that puts me first for next year.
He said, oh, no, you got to apply all over again.
So I applied all over again and wasn't selected anymore.
I wasn't selected, so I never did get in.
And then that's when I got in the insurance business.
If you turn your tape off, I'll tell you why I didn't get in.
What about the other universities?
Academically, I couldn't, I didn't meet some of their requirements.
Now, Tech University said, I met them, my academic grade was good.
Everything was fine.
My med, what is it, med sac?
Medical boards or whatever.
No, the med sac test.
Yeah.
MedPAC, MedSat.
Anyway, the medical aptitude test was good.
But they said I'd been in the war.
And my mind wasn't really acclimated to civilian life and I should go back to college for three years and then come back to them.
And I said, no, I can't do that.
Golly.
In fact, the war matured me.
I said, I'd be a better student.
That sounds like discrimination because you were
Because I got shot.
I got wounded.
And they said, no, your mind's all messed up and everything.
I said, you better go back to college.
For three years.
They wanted me to go three years and then come back.
I said, no.
Yeah, Dean Bailey.
I remember over here at Texas University.
I remember that well.
And then when I went up to Omaha, to Creighton, the dean said I was too old.
I was 27 or 28 years old.
I was too old.
So about four years, and then two years internship, that's six years, I'd be, what, 33?
34, 35 years old?
So, it was, you know, everybody had their reasons.
And it was frustrating.
Yeah, it was frustrating, so then I decided I won't try it anymore.
And I got an insurance business.
Do you feel bad about it?
You wanted to be a medical doctor.
You studied a science background at A&M.
Did you feel really let down or that you couldn't do that?
No, I don't.
I feel good.
I really do.
I wouldn't have met my wife.
I wouldn't have all my kids and the business and enjoy the community spirit here in Beaumont.
Oh, no.
It doesn't bother me.
It doesn't think.
It was just a good experience.
I mean, you know.
And, no, I
I wouldn't have been involved in the military like I have been.
Everything happens for the best.
So those are some of the things that you like and some of the things that you dislike about the Corps.
What about a position?
You were a leader ever since fifth grade.
What about a position of leadership in the Corps?
Were you a leader in the Corps?
I was not on the staff of any unit or anything.
I don't know why, come to think about it.
Yeah, I don't know.
Because you were on the staff of some of the other things.
Some of the other things, yeah.
I don't know why.
And I made A's in military A&M, where I was an average student in my other grades, sciences, chemistry, and zoology.
Yeah, now that I think about it, I had never thought about it that I was what they call a one-button in, you know, lieutenant in the unit.
But I was...
Never on the staff or anything.
Okay.

In what ways did thinking back about your career, not only in the military but also in the society and the insurance business, in what ways did the Corps help you and in what ways do you think it hindered you, if any?
It helped me.
It helped train me to be self-disciplined.
Okay.
It helped me, if I had a job to do, to do it.
and to do the best job I can with it.
It helped me to understand my fellow man, too.
In what way?
At A&M, in the Corps, when I saw some of the freshmen who, you know, it was pretty hard for them to take some of this hazing, I felt for them.
You know, I wanted to help him.
And I would.
In the same way in the military.
I wasn't a hard-nosed officer type who just ran over you because I knew I could run over you.
But I felt a little respect for the man.
I don't care what he was.
I tried to help him.
And yet I maintained my disciplinary position.
Because that's the position I held, and I was trying to uphold that, regardless if I was a captain, or a major, or a lieutenant colonel, or a general.
More so, when I got to be a general, I was more understanding.
Well, why do you think that is?
I guess because you're older?
Older.
Older.
Yeah.
And also, they look at you differently, too, as a general as they would a colonel or lieutenant colonel.
They look at you with more respect and more admiration.
And so if you feel that coming from the others, then you've got to respond to it in a more of an understanding manner, a more...
humility, a compassion type thing, as a general officer.
And I was a hard driver.
I drove.
I mean, I was aggressive all the way up the line.
Because I believed in doing the job and doing it as best I could.
And I pushed hard.
But when I got to be a general, I wasn't hard.
I looked at it a little bit differently.
Of course, I was looked at differently.
When I was battalion commander, we had three or four other battalion commanders, field artillery commanders in the division.
And I had to work hard because it was very competitive.
with these other commanders.
I had to shoot better than they did.
I had to move better than they did.
I had to communicate better.
That's it.
Shoot, move, and communicate.
That's field artillery.
And so I worked pretty hard.
In fact, Butler was one of the commanders.
Yeah.
Yeah, he was in the same division I was with.
Did he mention that to you, that we were together?
I guess he did.
Yeah, he probably did, but I did his interview last summer.
Oh, gosh.
See, Kidwell was our division commander.
But the A&M So the Corps helped you in those ways, but did it hinder you in any way, do you think?
Was there anything thatusually this is a difficult question.
Did it hold you back, or did it hurt your career or advancement in any way, do you think?
Let me say this, it helped me for me to understand the chain of command.
A&M helped me there.
As far as hindering and hurting, gee, I don't know.
I can't, I don't know where it could hurt me.
Okay, fine.
Except maybe while I was in the Corps, I didn't devote enough time to my other studies.
Right.
Yeah.
Except, now that's the day and end, but after I got out, I can't recall any time where the Corps gave me any bad points, you know, in the military or in life or anywhere.
Okay.
Now this is kind of interesting that you were a leader before you got to the Corps.
During the Corps you weren't.
Did you think that the Corps had any effect on your becoming a future leader, a general?
I never thought of it when I was at A&M, why I wasn't on a leadership spot.
I just, I guess my time was taken up by being a leader on the basketball team.
Satisfied, satisfied my... Because you were.
I was.
That's right.
You ran the basketball team.
I ran the basketball team.
That's right.
Because some of the generals that I talked to ran some part of the Corps, and because you were an athlete, you ran the basketball team.
I ran the basketball team.
So I was satisfied as far as being envious of a person being on the brigade staff or regimental staff or battalion staff.
So it really didn't bother me.
I wasn't ever jealous of someone's position.
Now there has been talk, especially during the Vietnam War, I think was the most recent time in American history, but before that, of the so-called military mentality.
People in the military think a certain way.
They have the same idea.
All the bureaucrats think the same way, all the people in the military.
Do you think there is a so-called military mentality?
There is, but not with A&M men.
Because I line that up with stereotyped thinking.
And A&M men are not stereotyped thinking on the whole.
Now, there may be some exceptions.
The military in Vietnam, that show was a regular Army show.
It wasn't a reserve show.
Okay.
But I don't want to just, I mean, I don't want to just use Vietnam.
Yeah.
I just, but what I'm interested in is just this idea that people in the military think a certain way.
I've heard this before.
That's right.
Like people in the bureaucracies, they all think the same way.
And some people in the students, they all think the same way.
Everybody stereotypes everybody.
And I was wondering if you thought that there's such a thing as this military mentality.
There is.
And what is it?
Could you define it?
I don't know how you would define something like that, Terry.
Well, what does someone in the military think versus the way other people think?
They have no flexibility.
Oh, okay.
So part of it is...
It's an adjustment to the situation.
They come up on a situation and they say, this is the solution, period.
Boom.
That's military thinking.
When it could be, if they would give it some adjustment, I mean, some thinking and evaluation and,
and some, it could be other means to accomplish what they want to do without just a stereo 1-2-3 army type.
Yeah, there is military mentality.
I run across that lots of times.
And you think that the A&M officers aren't, they don't have this mentality as much as other officers?
Is that what you were saying?
That's what I'm saying.
They don't have this...
A military mentality.
That's what makes an A&M graduate a good officer because he's not set in concrete in his military thinking.
Okay.
He's more flexible.
More flexible.
He tries to get the best solution, not the solution.
Okay.
Not the Army solution.
When people talk about military mentality, they also talk about the Army way or the Army solution to a problem.
But an A&M man, you say, is more flexible.
More flexible.
What was your opinion of your professors back at A&M from 1939 to 1943?
Well, I liked them all.
Of course, I was trained to like your teachers and like your professors.
That's the way I was raised.
Papa raised us that way.
You know, respect for your teacher.
And I don't know of any outstanding teachers except one, I guess, Dr. Ichfeldt, my English professor.
He amazed me.
One day he walked into class, first day he walked into class, and 33 of us were in there, and he called the roll.
He made us all hold our hand up, and he looked at us, and then he turned the roll upside down, and he called everybody by name.
After that, oh, that impressed me more than anything in the world.
Dr. Ickefeldt, English professor.
I think he still lives on campus.
He's retired.
But I was, I don't know.
Did you feel that the education prepared you for the future?
Looking back, yeah, I guess it did.
Of course, I was taking the pre-med course.
It didn't prepare me for the insurance business, except it trained my mind, education.
I had a prof. Yeah, I'll give you an adverse remark.
Dr. Potter.
was my pre-medical advisor.
And he didn't like the idea that I played basketball.
I would, at 5 o'clock, I'd close my lab book up or my cap, put it away, and, where you going, Mike?
I'm going to play basketball.
Now, either you're going to play basketball or be a doctor, what?
I said, if I quit basketball, I can't go to school because I need the scholarship to...
So he didn't...
So...
He taught me to have a little humility for people, not to be so hard on you.
He was hard on me, hard as he could be.
In fact, I think he was mean, come to think about it.
Really?
Yeah, he was mean to me.
And he was my pre-med advisor.
I had to get his recommendation to get medical school.
And I didn't get it.
Really?
No, he wouldn't give it to me.
Even though my grades were, you know, average, good.
He wouldn't guess, no.
Which I thought was unfair.
Yeah.
Why would he be your advisor if he wouldn't help you out in the future?
I don't know.
He was, that school designated him as our pre-med advisor.
Let's talk for a minute about, in the Army, the quality of A&M graduates versus West Point graduates versus ROTC
from other institutions.
Could you compare those?
Yes, very easy.
You could always tell a West Point graduate because he was really stiff, and I'm not using this as a cliche, but he was stiff, wasn't warm, and sort of an ego type thing.
And then the other ROTCs just didn't have the military discipline
that A&M ROTC graduates had.
Dress, courtesies, bearing.
I could spot them.
I could tell.
Because I had staffs of mixed Georgia Tech graduates, Auburn graduates, A&M graduates, and I could tell.
Yet they were just as intelligent as an A&M graduate or West Point, but they just didn't have the
military barracks.
And yet the West Pointer had the military band, but he went beyond that.
He was sort of a zealot?
Kind of pompous?
Pompous type.
Couldn't talk to him.
You couldn't talk to him about anything except military.
And then they weren't too versed on that except what they learned at West Point.
They always talked about West Point.
But
A&M, man, you can talk to them about anything.
Business, world affairs, government.
And when you got the military, he knew just as much about the military as the West Point man did.
Or more.

The field artillery, I know in the field artillery, when I went to report in my first division, 8th Armored Division, as a field artilleryman, I had to teach the West Point graduate how to fire a small T. Really?
Yeah, he didn't know.
Didn't they have practical training like that?
Not at West Point.
They sent them to school at Fort Sill.
While at A&M, they trained you for four years as an orfeal artilleryman.
And they did send you to Fort Sill, Oklahoma, the artillery school.
But the West Pointer, he just didn't have that specialty of that.
And same thing about infantrymen or cavalrymen or coast artillery or the engineers at A&M.
They knew their field.
They knew.
That was their branch, and they knew it.
But even the other ROTC schools knew more about their specialty than the West Point.
When you were out in the field, who would you rather have as your officer?
What type?
The West Point ROTC or an Aggie?
Which one would you rather have?
Aggie.
I preferred Aggie all the time.
And when you were a general, which one?
Aggie.
Aggie again.
Oh, yeah.
One time I had a field artillery battalion, all Aggies, except one Georgia Tech graduate.
Really?
That's right.
